values:
The townsfolk moved with a purpose that belied their circumstances. Their homes had been taken from them so recently, and they were moving into an uncertain future. But the intimate closeness the town had--plus the assurance that a highly skilled troop of soldiers was watching their every move--gave a certain levity to their journey. They talked, and speculated, and gossiped as always.

On the edge of this, a tense confrontation was breaking out between two of the swordsmen sworn to protect the village. It was not a battle of steel, but of keen observation and heightened senses, a mental duel of awareness.

&quot;I spy, with my little eye...&quot;

&quot;A tree.&quot;

&quot;Aw, come on, Dar. No fair!&quot;

&quot;Seiryu, you've been cycling between tree, dirt, rock, and sky for the last twenty rounds. Not much else out here. I think we need to find another game.&quot;

&quot;Errr...&quot; Seiryu scratched his scalp thoughtfully, sending shivers of motion down the long smooth strands of his hair. &quot;I'm not sure I know many games that we can play as we walk.&quot;

&quot;It's true, most of the boredom relievers out there are meant to be played sitting down.&quot; Dar clicked his tongue on the roof of his mouth, a pensive habit that he had picked up from an old friend. &quot;Oh, I've got one. Have you ever played Green Gnome, Red Gnome?&quot;

&quot;I've heard of it.&quot;

&quot;Okay, so it's a sort of mental dice game. First, you think of a number...&quot;

His explanation was cut short by a shriek from in front of the two men. Dar and Seiryu, already on edge, drew their swords and raised them in unison, all sinew and muscle and focus.

A dark-haired feminine figure in white robes, ahead of them, was falling to the ground. In the moments that it happened, Dar knew something was not quite right, and not quite dangerous, about this fall: the woman fell ever too slowly, and a pointy rock on the ground in her area of imminent impact seemed to scoot itself out of harm's way at the last second. As it was, she was able to catch herself on her hands.

The trip slowed her on her journey momentarily, and so Dar and Seiryu caught up. &quot;Ma'am? Are you okay?&quot;

&quot;Oof. I'm alright. And don't call me ma'am, I'd like to think my youth isn't quite over.&quot; An attractive woman in her early thirties, Petra Moran turned to face the pair of Legionnaires and looked them up and down approvingly. &quot;You're both quite the dashing sorts, aren't you?&quot;

&quot;Both?&quot; Dar chuckled. &quot;Usually it's just Ladykiller here who gets the attention from women.&quot; A few seconds later than he should have, he noticed her unique style of dress. &quot;And isn't that a little out of place for a priestess to be saying?&quot;

&quot;Dashing?&quot; Seiryu mumbled under his breath, not really following the flow of conversation.

&quot;I'm a priestess of Tymora,&quot; she explained, as if that was the only explanation necessary.

&quot;Haven't heard of him. Her? It?&quot;

&quot;Her. She's a luck goddess.&quot; Petra reached inside her robed and pulled out a talisman on a chain. The talisman was a coin, both sides of which bore the profile of her smiling deity. &quot;And as luck is one of those things that follows those who live full and fulfilling lives... My order isn't particularly keen on restrictive strictures.&quot; She winked at him. &quot;Unlike your line of work, I'm sure.&quot;

&quot;Hey, now,&quot; Dar began defensively, &quot;if we did nothing but follow orders we wouldn't be here.&quot;

She laughed again. Dar thought that she had quite a nice laugh. Must be all the luck she lived with. &quot;I figured as much. You look like a bit of a rogue... more so than a rank-and-file hack-and-slash fellow, anyway.&quot;

&quot;He was a rogue, once,&quot; Seiryu chimed in. &quot;Ran away from home to work for the mob and everything.&quot;

Petra raised an eyebrow.

&quot;Thank you, Seiryu,&quot; Dar muttered in mild irritation. &quot;Hey, don't look at me like that. My parents were horrible, and I didn't hurt anyone who didn't need hurting.&quot;

&quot;Hey, I wouldn't be one to judge. My father was a mage of some renown, and... well, let's just say you know you're a strange sort of teenager when your idea of rebellion is to run off and join a religious movement.&quot;

&quot;Well, at least she's a luck goddess, right?&quot; Seiryu grinned. &quot;You could have done a lot worse things!&quot;

&quot;I wasn't brought into the fold of Tymora's grace until much later,&quot; she said regretfully. &quot;This was a... different sort of religious movement.&quot;

Something about the domain of Petra's goddess finally clicked in Dar's brain. &quot;Luck... That's how you avoided that fall!&quot;

&quot;Tymora's grace does occasionally protect me from harm without my conscious intent, yes. One of the little perks of taking up the oath.&quot;

&quot;Oath?&quot; Sei asked. &quot;But I thought you said your order wasn't restrictive.&quot;

&quot;The oath mainly binds us to worship Tymora and spread good news and good fortune wherever we go,&quot; she said. &quot;Also, we're not allowed to gamble, but that's more of a fairness issue than anything.&quot;

Dar started to say something, but Seiryu's hand on his shoulder quieted him. &quot;Dar. Something's happening.&quot;

Dar had long since learned that, as a sergeant, trusting his men's senses was the best way to keep them all alive. In addition, Seiryu's ears were famously sensitive. &quot;What is it?&quot;

&quot;Sounds like a fight. Something else going on, too, something strange.&quot;

Just then there was a loud swooshing sound and a flash of light, like... well, like something strange.

Four fighting men and a balding mage in a blood-red cloak stepped out of the strange something approximately twenty feet away from Dar and Seiryu's position.

&quot;Oh, hey,&quot; Dar quipped tersely. &quot;A fight.&quot;

Two of the fighters pulled off to the sides to allow the other two--archers, they saw now--to pull back and take aim. Dar and Seiryu saw this happening and feinted to either side. The arrows went wide. Clearly the archers had not been expecting this level of sophistication in their opponents, but that was sure to change.

The swordsmen made their rush to cover the archers, who were nocking their next rounds, and the mage, who was chanting. Rather than do the smart thing and gang up, one went at Sei and one at Dar. Dar muttered a couplet under his breath--it was very unpolished and spur-of-the-moment so he wasn't keen on saying it out loud--and stabbed his blade along the length of his attacker's arm, hooking it under the elbow and using the blade as a lever to torque the sword into the ground. Before his assailant's eyes could even widen in shock, he stepped on the middle of the other man's sword, bending it and tugging the man down into the dirt in one action, before kicking the bent sword off where it could do no harm. Having mostly neutralized the threat, he neatly quickstepped over the fallen soldier in the direction of the mage.

Seiryu didn't take Dar's precise approach to the problem, instead favoring a more direct approach. He brought his sword up for a chop, leading his opponent to attack his undefended midsection, but instead sidestepped and rammed the pointy, heavy hilt of his blade into the goon's nose. The soldier dropped like a sack of cement and Seiryu rushed onwards.

There was a flashing, sizzling noise and Dar's view of the world exploded in a shower of sparks and fire. The lightning bolt forked from the mage's fingertips to both Dar and Seiryu... as well as the two archers and, curling back in an improbable way, the mage himself. The trailing shower of sparks in the wake of the bolt showed its path--it was also heading towards some of the villagers and Petra, but twisted backwards. Dar and Seiryu, both wearing metal chain maille, couldn't have been spared by any amount of luck.

Even though every one of his nerves was on fire from the electric onslaught, Seiryu staggered forward. Fortunately for him, the archer was just as twitchy in the aftereffects of the bolt as he was, so he didn't have time to aim for a chink in Seiryu's breastplate. Unfortunately, the arrow struck dead on, dead center, transmitting about a hundred pounds of force like a good solid punch to the breastplate.

Dar's archer was smarter, and aimed for the head. His aim was heavily disrupted as well, and the arrow grazed Dar's ear.

Both archers, being otherwise unable to defend themselves, fell quickly to the enraged Legionnaires. Soon they were facing the red-robed mage, all three of them blackened and crispy.

The mage, not having another spell that he could use safely, took a step backwards away from the two men. His foot caught on the ground and he tripped, hard.

Dar could have sworn he saw a very dangerous-looking rock appear under the man's head as he fell, twisting, faster than gravity alone would have allowed.

The two swordsmen looked up from the fortuitously incapacitated shaman to see Petra Moran in the thick of battle, holding her two-headed coin out in front of her like a ward.

Seiryu's jaw fell open, partially in shock and partially to catch his breath. &quot;That was you?&quot;

Dar laughed as much as his spasming muscles would allow. &quot;Let me guess. Tymora's fortune doesn't visit itself on those who are trying to kill her servants?&quot;

Petra smiled widely as she put the coin away. &quot;Lucky guess.&quot;

